As mass falls toward a black hole from some far distance, it loses gravitational potential energy (i.e. it’s gravitational potential energy becomes less negative). The more massive and compact the object the mass is accreting onto the more gravitational potential energy it loses. In fact, if we view the mass as coming from infinity, the amount of gravitational potential energy lost by the accreting matter is (GMm/(2GM/c^2)) = ½ mC^2. This is half the rest mass energy of the object. As this massive amount of energy is lost by the accreting matter, some of it is given off in the form of light.
